{"type":"message","id":"bb10d828","parentId":"7dbe1614","timestamp":"2026-04-13T06:26:32.243Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants a fallback mechanism to ensure that when they start a /new session, I'll remember \"this thing\" (the framework fixes and memory system we just worked on). \n\nThe user is concerned that the bootstrap injection might not work (since it's never been verified). They want a \"保底\" (fallback/insurance) mechanism.\n\nThe simplest and most reliable fallback: write a prominent reminder directly into a file that I check on every startup - like MEMORY.md itself, which is already supposed to be read at startup according to AGENTS.md.\n\nBut the problem is AGENTS.md's bootstrap instructions aren't automatically executed by the system.\n \nSo the real issue is that even though AGENTS.md tells me to read MEMORY.md at startup, I'm not actually doing it—I need to verify whether the system is injecting MEMORY.md automatically or if I need to rely on my own compliance with the AGENTS.md rules.\n\nGiven that there's no way to test this in the current session, the safest approach is to make MEMORY.md as complete and self-contained as possible, so that even if I'm just following AGENTS.md instructions manually, I'll still have everything I need. I should also create a high-visibility marker in the file—a clear \"LAST SESSION SUMMARY\" section that would stand out and prompt me to reference the session files if my memory fails.","thinkingSignature":"7b9350f253d1ca432af523c28e414313f3f9d82beb6e358d434706c6e21d35ca"},{"type":"text","text":"最可靠的保底：**MEMORY.md 本身就是启动时就应该读的文件**。\n\n只要 AGENTS.md 的规则被系统执行，MEMORY.md 就会被注入。我已经把所有关键内容写进去了：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_j883n4gittvl_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/ai/.openclaw/workspace/MEMORY.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":54,"output":353,"cacheRead":40495,"cacheWrite":117,"totalT