{"type":"message","id":"a2d1a123","parentId":"eb009649","timestamp":"2026-04-13T06:30:24.238Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see - process 65569 is still running (from before, I couldn't kill it because it was protected or something). And the new process died because it couldn't bind to 3104. And it says port 8080 in the log... but wait, the log shows \"starting on port 8080\" which is from the print statement, but the actual uvicorn.run is on port 3104. So the new process tried 3104, failed (gateway was there), then exited.\n\nWait, looking more carefully at the log: the new process log shows it tried to start on port 8080 (from the print statement). But the actual code has port 3104 hardcoded. \n\nSo the log is confusing me - it's showing the print output before the port is determined. Let me trace through what's actually happening: the old process (65569) is still on 3105, the new process starts but can't bind to 3104 because gateway has it, and then it shuts down. The issue is that `python3 api_server.py` runs from whichever directory the script is in, not from where bash is executed. Since run_ws2.sh contains a cd command, the working directory changes before python runs, so the process is looking for api_server.py in the wrong location.\n\nWait, but I already checked the working directory and it's definitely pointing to the v8 version of scene-classifier, not the workspace version. So either the process actually is the v8 version despite what I thought, or there's something else going on with which api_server.py is being executed.\n\nLooking back at the logs more carefully - there's only one \"Loaded embedding classifier\" message in the recent output, and it came from the workspace directory. That means the old process from before must have already exited, and what I'm seeing now is a fresh startup attempt that's failing to bind to the port.\n\nThe real issue is that the workspace version's api_server.py has the port hardcoded to 3104, but gateway is already using that port. There's no fallback mechanism, so the new instance just crashes. I could modify the script to dynamically find an available port, but the cleaner approach would be to just restart the gateway - if I kill it first, the workspace server can bind to 3104 before gateway restarts.","thinkingSignature":"330d0614ee861100537299d25947217d5aa74aca3f22e502d01fd66866d51a00"},{"type":"text","text":"gateway 占着 3104，workspace 版本无法启动。改用可用端口策略：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_wf6nw290lrzz_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/ai/.openclaw/workspace/skills/scene-classifier/api_server.py","offset":100,"limit":15}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":30609,"output":551,"cacheRead":18037,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":49197,"cost":{"input":0.0091827,"output":0.0006611999999999999,"cacheRead":0.0010822199999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.010926120000000001}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776061806619,"responseId":"062bc06d7d336d56d22d585b1fce820c"}}
