{"type":"message","id":"302eb68d","parentId":"a5271b3d","timestamp":"2026-04-13T06:35:20.719Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The workspace version still didn't start. The script might have exited. Let me check the log.\n\nWait - the script starts a python3 -c process which then starts api_server.py as a subprocess. The subprocess might have failed because the workspace api_server.py tries to bind to 3104 first. But the log says it successfully started on 3108 before being shut down.\n\nActually, looking at the log again:\n```\nINFO:     Uvicorn running on http://0.0.0.0:3108 (Press CTRL+C to quit)\nINFO:     127.0.0.1:39820 - \"POST /classify HTTP/1.1\" 200 OK\n\n\n```\n\nSo the workspace version was running on 3108 and successfully served a request before being shut down when the gateway restarted. The gateway was restarting multiple times across different processes (64417, 66767, 66776, 66872), and each restart was killing the previous instances. When the last gateway restart happened, it cleaned up all the old processes including the workspace scene-classifier that was still trying to bind to 3108.\n\nNow I'm noticing that v8 (pid 66439) is somehow still running on 3105 even though I thought I killed it earlier with `kill 65569`. The timestamps don't make sense - this process started at 14:30 but I killed the old v8 process much earlier. Let me trace through the actual sequence of events to figure out which process is which.\n\n```\n- 65569 killed at ~14:28\n- run_ws2.sh started new processes\n- 66404 = workspace version, later killed\n- 66439 = v8 version that somehow survived\n- workspace version died at some point\n```\n\nActually, the real issue is that I can't reliably kill 66439 because it's the v8 version, and if I do, systemd will just restart it and reclaim 3105. Let me check the current state and see what's actually listening on which port.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to ensure the workspace version binds to 3108 and just accept that v8 will stay on 3105. But I'm seeing 66439 with a start time of 14:30, which suggests it's been running since before my last restart attempt. I should just verify what's currently bound to each port and proceed from there.","thinkingSignature":"aa170817c57278a78f1cb1bd8bd7421af106ed2524be0a15953f09817c46f74c"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_njp1b2090dou_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /tmp/sc_ws.log 2>/dev/null | tail -10"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":32942,"output":525,"cacheRead":18127,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":51594,"cost":{"input":0.0098826,"output":0.0006299999999999999,"cacheRead":0.0010876199999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.01160022}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776062101760,"responseId":"062bc195baec23a94e06c8794423d266"}}
